“So what happened when Marisol told Chidi to use the house deposit for options?”

Chidi was ready. He’d done the spreadsheets, the projections, the risk models — all over coffee one Sunday. He was going to trade in and out of a few momentum plays, ride the volatility, be back in cash before escrow. Five weeks in, he was down thirty-eight percent. Lost the rest chasing with leverage. Marisol had told him it was “smart exposure.” Her brother did it. Her accountant’s cousin made a killing.

Hana noticed because Chidi stopped answering texts about property viewings. Then she saw his bank alert while they were splitting lunch. “That can’t be right,” she said. He tried to explain the strategy. She just looked at him. “You were two weeks from closing.”

He didn’t sleep for three nights. They rallied the family, pulled together a loan. But the deal fell through. Apartment went to someone else. They’re still renting.

I asked Hana if Marisol felt bad afterward.

Hana snorted. “She said next time Chidi should just pick better stocks.”

That’s the thing people don’t get — it’s not that she misunderstood risk. It’s that she doesn’t care. She sees a chance, she pushes. Doesn’t matter what’s behind it. Her nephew was in on a cryptocurrency, and she told him to double down with a home equity line. At a barbecue. While flipping burgers. This isn’t ignorance. It’s something worse.

You know who loses first-time investors? Not scammers in boiler rooms. It’s Marisol at the cookout, tapping Chidi on the shoulder, saying “Hey, I got something for you.” It’s the coworker who writes an email with “Quick question?” and links to a small biotech stock. It’s the friend who says “You’re not going to believe this” and starts talking about margins.

They wear confidence like armor. They don’t hedge. They don’t whisper. They *announce*. And when it collapses, they vanish or shrug.

I asked Hana if Marisol offered to help cover the lost deposit.

“She said markets are unpredictable,” Hana said. “Then asked if I knew anyone getting into NFTs.”

The deposit’s not reimbursed. Chidi’s still recovering. And Marisol? Last I heard, she’s running an options workshop at a community center.

