Dmitri had saved nineteen months for a down payment—$68,000 in a high-yield account, socked away while living on canned beans and avoiding every happy hour. He wanted a two-bedroom near the library, quiet, no dogs. Ingrid saw the number in his finance app while they were splitting a bottle of wine. “You’re just… letting it sit?” she said, like he’d confessed to feeding money to pigeons. 

Chidi overheard at the barbecue two weeks later. “Dmitri. Buddy.” He leaned in, spat a piece of corn off his fork. “You know what makes real returns? Options. Thirty bucks turns into three grand if a biotech stock gaps at open. I made six months’ rent last quarter. Tax-free.” He winked. “You’re not *saving*, man. You’re losing.”

It wasn’t just Chidi. Dmitri’s coworker had done it. So had a guy on a podcast. Ingrid started calling him “Grandpa Fund” when he hesitated. The market had been climbing all spring—everyone said volatility was low, corrections were dead. Even the broker at Dmitri’s bank shrugged when he asked. “If you’ve got the risk tolerance…”

He put $15,000 into a short-dated call on a cryptocurrency-adjacent semiconductor play. The stock dropped twenty-seven percent in one afternoon after a supply-chain rumor. The option expired Friday. Worth zero come Monday.

Ingrid didn’t mention it. Chidi said, “Lesson learned,” at a party, loud enough for Dmitri to hear over the music, then went back to pouring whiskey.

Dmitri still drives past the building where the unit was. Fourth floor, east-facing. He’s back to saving. Cans again.  

“Worth the risk?” someone asked him last week.

He just looked at them.

