Ingrid pulled up the chart on her phone like it was a winning lottery ticket. “Look,” she said, jabbing at the screen. “Kofi made 18% in two weeks. On options. On that little biotech stock. He didn’t even tie up much capital.” We were in Marisol’s kitchen, wine half-finished, the kind of evening where money talk creeps in like humidity. Marisol had been saving two years for a down payment. Seventy-two thousand, salted away, boring and safe. Now here was Ingrid, convinced that letting that cash “sleep” was the real risk.

Kofi had framed it as a one-off, “just one contract,” treat it like bonus money. But you don’t say that to someone who doesn’t know the difference between a call and a calendar spread. You don’t plant that idea when the rent is due, when friends are closing on units downtown, when the market’s been climbing and everyone smells easy money. He wasn’t some boiler-room shark. He wore the same hiking boots to work every Thursday, talked about his kid’s piano recitals. That’s what makes these people worse. They’re not hiding. They’re at your barbecue, nodding sagely, saying “You’re too risk-averse” like it’s a character flaw.

The review isn’t about the book anymore, really. It’s about the way people use scraps of financial literacy like weapons. The book — you know the one, big yellow cover, subtitle about “embracing volatility” — pretends to be about risk management. But it’s written in the same smug, detached voice that makes blowing through a down payment seem like a “learning experience.” There’s a whole chapter that says, and I’m not exaggerating, that “illiquid milestones can be reframed as opportunity costs.” Reframed. Like anxiety and rent denial aren’t real things. Like Kofi, when Marisol messaged him two weeks later — account down 38%, panic setting in — didn’t just reply, “Maybe exit now?” as if he’d forgotten she was using grocery money.

She didn’t lose everything. Not yet. But she pulled half out. “To stabilize,” she said. As if the damage wasn’t already metabolic, like a fever that won’t break. I saw her at the bank yesterday, filling out a form. Said the loan officer gave her a weird look when she explained the gap in her savings. Kofi texted her last night: “Market’s ripe for a bounce. Still time to average up.”

