------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Felix sat across from me at lunch last week, grinning like he’d cracked the code. “Dmitri doubled his money in three weeks,” he said, “and he started with less than you.” He didn’t mention the margin loan. Didn’t mention that Dmitri lost it all two days later when that small biotech stock tanked after bad trial results. Didn’t mention Dmitri’s credit card is maxed out paying off the broker’s emergency call.

This is the garbage you get when some guy who read half a finance blog and watched one YouTube video about “leveraging opportunities” decides he’s qualified to tell you how to invest. Noor mentioned her cousin gave her the same pitch at a barbecue—“just borrow a little, ride the wave,” like it’s surfing, not financial suicide. You know who talks like that? Brokers in movies. Or people who are either too dumb to understand risk or too eager to impress to care.

Here’s the reality: margin trading as a beginner is like learning to swim by jumping off a cliff. Most people don’t realize their broker can liquidate everything—your gains, your original investment, even parts of your account you didn’t touch—if the market dips 15 percent. You don’t get a warning. You don’t get to explain. You’re just wiped out, and now you owe money.

And the people giving this advice? They vanish. Dmitri called Felix three times after the blowup. Got silence. That’s because these people don’t stand by their “tips.” They’re not mentors. They’re not even well-meaning idiots. They’re the kind of person who’ll hand you a lit match and say “light this candle,” not mentioning your whole house is doused in gasoline.

If you’re just starting, your job isn’t to double your money next month. It’s to still have money next year. Put your cash in a low-cost index fund. Set up automatic contributions. Let it sit. Not exciting? Good. Excitement is what they sell to suckers.

And if someone leans in, lowers their voice, and says “you should really consider leveraging your position,” run. Not walk. Run. They don’t care if you lose everything. They care about feeling smart for five minutes. That’s the worst kind of person to listen to—one who treats your financial survival as their ego snack.

I had a guy at the gym last month—works in sales—told me a cryptocurrency he was “98 percent sure” would 10x. Said I’d regret not getting in. I didn’t. He wouldn’t tell me when I saw him again. Just mumbled something about “market conditions.” Of course. The ones giving dangerous advice always have a reason why it didn’t work—except the real one: they were never qualified to speak in the first place.

Noor, you asked what to do instead of margin trading. Open the account. Fund it. Buy one broad-market ETF. Set a monthly deposit. Then forget it exists. Do that for five years. Then talk to me about “opportunities.”  
“Felix said maybe just a small position,” she said.

