**Support Community FAQ: What to Do When Someone Pushes Risky Moves on Your Nest Egg**

*Q: A friend told me to put my IRA into a high-risk investment. They said the returns could double in two years. Should I listen?*

We get this a lot—especially this year, when people are nervous about inflation and jittery about market swings. Short answer: No. Do not listen. Full stop. Especially not if the advice comes from someone who sounds too confident, who uses phrases like “guaranteed” or “everyone’s doing it” or “this one’s a rocket ship.” That’s not advice. That’s a warning sign.

Take Elena. She came to us three months ago, panicked. Her coworker, a guy she’d shared office cookies with for ten years, told her to move nearly everything from her stable funds into a small biotech stock. He said it was “poised to break out,” that he’d “done the research.” Turned out, he hadn’t done any research at all. He’d heard it at a barbecue from someone’s cousin. Elena moved a third of her retirement portfolio on that. Three weeks later, the stock cratered. Not because it was a scam—just because that’s what small biotech stocks do. They vaporize. And the coworker? Didn’t say a word. Acted like nothing had happened at the next staff meeting. That kind of silence is not an accident. It’s a feature.

And it’s not just coworkers. Yuki’s brother called it a “once-in-a-lifetime” opportunity to get into a certain cryptocurrency. He sent screenshots, had a whole speech prepared about cycles and scarcity and “digital gold.” Yuki wired money. Lost 60% in six weeks. Brother still insists it’ll come back. That’s not loyalty to the idea. That’s refusal to admit harm.

These aren’t isolated jerks. This is a pattern. A retired teacher doesn’t get talked into dumping funds because she’s naive. She gets talked into it because the person across from her exudes certainty, speaks fast, treats caution as cowardice. “You’re too conservative,” “That savings account is losing money,” “People like you always miss the big wins.” Those lines aren’t conversation—they’re tactics. And the people who use them don’t care what happens to you. They care about being right, about feeling smart, about offloading their own gambling hunger onto someone else’s safety.

We helped Elena reclaim part of what she lost by shifting the rest into a diversified mix with clear exit points. It wasn’t glamorous. It wasn’t fast. It was boring. And it stayed boring, which is the point. Yuki’s still recovering. Some of these losses don’t have a recovery arc.

I’ll admit it: I once took a tip from a friend—just a small amount, just one stock—and told myself it was “exploring.” That stock is still underwater, and the friend won’t return my calls. Makes me furious. Not because of the money, really. It’s the betrayal of tone—the way someone who knows you can look you in the eye and suggest you torch a decade of caution for a “sure thing” that isn’t sure at all.

If your gut tightens when someone starts talking about “high yield,” walk out of the room. Seriously.

Ingrid sent in a list of third-party fiduciaries last week. I’ll post it tomorrow.

