So Owen’s at the grill, right. July. Smells like lighter fluid and burnt buns. He’s got sauce on his thumb and says, “Devon, you cashed out your 401(k) yet?”

I’m like, “What? No.”

He shakes his head. Slow. Like I just said I enjoy stepping on LEGOs. “You’re bleeding opportunity cost, man. You see what that small biotech’s doing? Up seventy last week. My cousin’s girlfriend made twenty-three grand in three days.”

No one asked him to say this. He just… did. Because the air felt warm. Because the market had crept up for, like, nine straight days. Because for three minutes, it somehow made sense to mortgage your future on a stock that could vanish if one lab result flops.

Sanjay did it. Cashed out half his retirement. Bought into a cryptocurrency because the “momentum was undeniable.” Sold his index funds “to avoid dead weight.” Owen clapped for him at the cookout like he’d run a marathon.

Two weeks later, that biotech stock? Down eighty-five. Sanjay’s portfolio worth less than his broken laptop.

I asked Owen if he felt bad.

He said, “Markets correct. He should’ve doubled down.”

That’s when you know. It’s not greed. It’s not ignorance. It’s that they *like* telling you what to do with your life. They stand there, handing out financial IEDs like party favors, then wonder why the room exploded.
